crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a Linux botnet agent, likely a variant of the Gafgyt (Bashlite) or Mirai family, designed for DDoS attacks and remote command execution. Key malicious behaviors include: 1. Network C2 Communication: It establishes a socket connection to a hardcoded C2 server at 158.94.210.71. 2. DDoS Attack Modules: Several functions (sub_402c66, sub_4022d6, sub_4017eb) are dedicated to generating high-volume network traffic, including TCP floods and game-server-specific attacks (SAMP/multiplayer protocol). 3. Competition Removal: The binary scans the /proc/ directory to identify and terminate (sub_4082f4/SIGKILL) other processes, a common tactic for removing competing malware or security tools. 4. Environment Fingerprinting: It reads /proc/cpuinfo and process command lines to identify the host environment. 5. Persistence/Stealth: It uses fork() and setsid() to daemonize itself and prctl() to potentially hide its process name. Relevant IOCs: C2 IP 158.94.210.71, /proc scanning, and raw socket manipulation.
